solution.p:
Using the above relationships, the x and y coordinates of the point are

 x \amp= r\cos(\theta) = 5\cos\left(\frac{2\pi}{3}\right)=5\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)=-\frac{5}{2}

 y \amp= r\sin(\theta) = 5\sin\left(\frac{2\pi}{3}\right)=5\left(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)=\frac{5\sqrt{3}}{2}

statement.p:
Shade the region described by the polar inequalities

 0 \amp\leq r \lt \infty 
 
 \frac{\pi}{6} \amp\leq \theta \leq \frac{\pi}{3}

solution.p:
Putting together these bounds for r and \theta gives us the polar inequalities

 0 \amp\leq r \leq 2 
 
 \frac{\pi}{2} \amp\leq \theta \leq \frac{4\pi}{3}

The shaded region stretches from the angle 3\pi/2 to the angle 5\pi/6. However, 3\pi/2 is greater than 5\pi/6, so in order to describe the shaded region, \theta cannot be greater than 3\pi/2 and less than 5\pi/6. Instead, we can use the angle -\pi/2 as our lower bound. This gives us the inequality
-\frac{\pi}{2} \leq \theta \leq \frac{5\pi}{6}
Notice that \theta can equal -\pi/2 and 5\pi/6, as represented by the solid lines. Putting together the bounds for r and \theta gives us the polar inequalities

 2 \amp\lt r \lt 3 
 
 -\frac{\pi}{2} \amp\leq \theta \leq \frac{5\pi}{6}
